Ecological and social indicators should be integrated into coherent frameworks used to evaluate sustainable urban mobility plans (SUMPs) and other policy documents. They can also be combined into social-ecological indicators: https://t.co/S4V1wnXLC6

The way the indicators are used is often problematic in an important way: they show a direction towards a more sustainable state, but not thresholds - e.g., reducing emissions without saying what emission level is fine. The rate of change is not enough, we should also set goals.

Sustainable mobility and transport justice/poverty fields are often in tension and tend to overlook "the other side" of the issue - the point also made by @giulio_mattioli and others here: https://t.co/CgQMhNWBxG

Here, we take the first steps towards defining a 'doughnut'/'corridor' for urban mobility by bringing together indicators from sustainable urban mobility (SUM, whose main focus is on environmental impacts) and transport poverty (whose main focus is on social justice) domains.

The basic idea of 'safe and just space' for a sector is defining its 'ecological ceiling' (EC) - maximum levels of environmental impacts and resource use that are sustainable - and 'social foundation' (SF) - providing for human needs in a socially just and equitable way https://t.co/tTDZdXZSf0

Probably the most important article that we published this year, in which we apply ideas like #DoughnutEconomics and "sustainable consumption corridors" to the urban mobility sector. Here is a üßµ about its main points:
https://t.co/kAQkFmbtQC
